>> NICOLAS STEENHOUT: Hi, everyone.

00:01:58.950 --> 00:02:01.200
Thank you for the intro, Amber.

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:02.580
I am Nic Steenhout.

00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:07.260
I'm so super excited to open the
WordPress Accessibility Day 2022.

00:02:08.370 --> 00:02:13.230
It's so awesome to see events
related to WordPress talking

00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:17.850
and educating about accessibility
because WordPress is big.

00:02:17.850 --> 00:02:19.470
We all know that.

00:02:19.470 --> 00:02:24.400
The other big thing is the number
of disabled people in the world.

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:27.210
I'll talk about the numbers
game in a bit, but first,

00:02:27.210 --> 00:02:31.600
a little bit more about
me that Amber was saying.

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:34.790
I've been working in digital
accessibility one way or another

00:02:34.790 --> 00:02:37.350
for a very long time.

00:02:37.350 --> 00:02:42.330
I remember when the alt
attribute was introduced to HTML.

00:02:42.330 --> 00:02:47.700
Trivia time, this was in 1993.

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:49.070
It's quite a while back.

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:54.470
When I was doing websites.

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:58.340
I was not really thinking about
accessibility at the time,

00:02:58.340 --> 00:03:04.620
but I had a bit of an Aha moment
and it came in three moments.

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:08.000
The first one was talking to
a colleague, he was blind.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.040
He came into my office one day,
he was so frustrated, he says,

00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:13.010
"Make this website."

00:03:13.010 --> 00:03:16.100
The only thing I hear is
image, image, image.

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:21.470
Then I looked at the site and
I realized what we were doing

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:23.960
at the time because
CSS was not a thing.

00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:29.160
To have really nice fonts
we would take image of text

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:34.190
and cut them out and then
present that as our menu

00:03:34.190 --> 00:03:36.920
or as our main text even.

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:40.150
We didn't put in alt text
and suddenly I realized,

00:03:40.150 --> 00:03:44.550
"Oh, this is a problem for someone
who's blind using a screen reader."

00:03:44.550 --> 00:03:47.994
It looks good,
but it's basically nonexistent

00:03:47.994 --> 00:03:49.280
for assistive technologies.

00:03:50.470 --> 00:03:56.020
The second moment, about two
weeks later, was a deaf colleague.

00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:58.650
She came into my
office and she said,

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:04.680
"Nic, I can't install this printer
because the instructions are

00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:09.520
on a CD with a video,
no text, and no captions."

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:14.490
I had to help setting up the printer
because the instructions were not

00:04:14.490 --> 00:04:15.810
in an accessible format.

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:23.550
Then the third time within again,
just a few more weeks later was

00:04:23.550 --> 00:04:28.850
one of our consumer came in and
she says, "I would love to be able

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:33.790
to use the web,
but everything is distracting me.

00:04:33.790 --> 00:04:38.510
All the colors, all the blinking
things, the text moving,

00:04:38.510 --> 00:04:43.480
the large font, the underline,
everything is so distracting

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:44.970
that I can't use it."

00:04:44.970 --> 00:04:48.570
I started looking,
how do we do this?

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:54.890
I created basically a CSS
reset before that was a thing

00:04:54.890 --> 00:04:58.010
for this person with ADHD.

00:04:58.010 --> 00:05:03.810
These three events, one after the
other, really cemented the importance

00:05:03.810 --> 00:05:06.130
of digital accessibility.

00:05:06.130 --> 00:05:08.880
As a wheelchair user,
I was already aware of

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:12.200
how important physical
accessibility was

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:16.320
and these three people
really brought it home to me.

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:24.420
These days I mostly provide
consultation for large companies.

00:05:24.420 --> 00:05:26.990
They aim to improve their
product accessibility.

00:05:26.990 --> 00:05:35.110
I've also done a lot of
work around open source,

00:05:35.110 --> 00:05:38.700
including using WordPress as a
developer and as an end user.

00:05:40.290 --> 00:05:45.000
I've been on the W3CA Accessibility
Initiative, the education,

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:46.970
and outreach working group.

00:05:46.970 --> 00:05:52.370
I've worked with and on open-source
applications for a long time

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:56.960
and now I prefer to provide
accessibility training.

00:05:56.960 --> 00:06:01.220
I speak about visibility, inclusion,
and obviously accessibility

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:02.690
at tech events like this one.

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:07.590
Though today my presentation
is not a tech talk

00:06:07.590 --> 00:06:12.930
because accessibility is not
about tech, it's about people.

00:06:12.930 --> 00:06:17.180
That's my main motive
today, my main message,

00:06:17.180 --> 00:06:19.970
and that's what I'm
going to talk about.

