00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:17.820
I was glad to see there's many
disabled presenters, organizers today

00:41:17.820 --> 00:41:19.550
at this conference.

00:41:19.550 --> 00:41:21.710
Maybe not all
disabilities are visible,

00:41:21.710 --> 00:41:25.780
but obviously disabled folks
have a keen interest in things

00:41:25.780 --> 00:41:26.780
being accessible.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:34.560
Disabled people are often called
on to be accessibility champion,

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:39.350
but we can get tired,
we're now frustrated, burned out.

00:41:39.350 --> 00:41:42.100
Think about my Joomla experience.

00:41:42.100 --> 00:41:42.940
Let's face it.

00:41:42.940 --> 00:41:46.850
Also, sometimes we want to do
stuff that's not directly related

00:41:46.850 --> 00:41:52.130
to accessibility, and too many
projects expect disabled people

00:41:52.130 --> 00:41:53.660
to help with accessibility.

00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:56.906
I had a developer who once tweet,

00:41:56.907 --> 00:41:59.460
"Hey, are there blind
screenreader users

00:41:59.460 --> 00:42:01.180
that want to help with my project?"

00:42:01.180 --> 00:42:02.940
There was no money in it.

00:42:02.940 --> 00:42:09.080
There was nothing other than I'm
going to use your time to tell me

00:42:09.080 --> 00:42:11.980
if my site works or not without
having done the background.

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:17.060
Too few projects are willing to
pay disabled people for their time,

00:42:17.060 --> 00:42:20.440
and by pay, I don't just mean
money, I'm talking about pay

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:26.060
with respect, pay with actual
changes, pay with listening to us.

00:42:28.720 --> 00:42:33.880
Now, accessibility champions
shouldn't just be disabled people

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:35.230
on a project.

00:42:35.230 --> 00:42:39.340
Yes, we want to be involved when
the circumstances are right,

00:42:39.340 --> 00:42:42.020
but we're not enough
of us to go around.

00:42:42.020 --> 00:42:46.030
We have a lot of people that are
disabled, but there's none of us

00:42:46.030 --> 00:42:49.530
to go and participate
in all these projects.

00:42:50.670 --> 00:42:53.840
Beyond champions, we need allies.

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:58.180
I know many non-disabled folks
working in accessibility, good folks,

00:42:58.180 --> 00:43:01.120
allies, accomplices,
champions, and experts.

00:43:01.120 --> 00:43:06.460
To those non-disabled folks watching
the presentation, thank you.

00:43:06.460 --> 00:43:08.500
Thank you for being
interested in accessibility.

00:43:08.500 --> 00:43:10.430
Thank you for your work.

00:43:10.430 --> 00:43:14.490
To the disabled folks watching,
let's make sure to give them a chance

00:43:14.490 --> 00:43:15.610
to be good allies.

00:43:17.930 --> 00:43:21.900
Also, let's remember that
being disabled doesn't make you

00:43:21.900 --> 00:43:25.120
an accessibility
expert, necessarily.

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:28.470
Being disabled makes you an
expert on your own experience

00:43:28.470 --> 00:43:30.810
of disability and accessibility.

00:43:30.810 --> 00:43:34.540
In some ways, being disabled
makes you the super expert

00:43:34.540 --> 00:43:38.410
on your own experience, and your
voice is very important for that.

00:43:40.820 --> 00:43:43.430
Unless you make an effort
to learn about other aspects

00:43:43.430 --> 00:43:45.920
of accessibility,
you can't be an expert.

00:43:45.920 --> 00:43:49.350
Unless you work hard at
it, you can't be an expert.

00:43:49.350 --> 00:43:53.910
I'm going to plug in my podcast
here, the accessibility soundbite

00:43:53.910 --> 00:43:57.570
